Understanding IAM in the SaaS Context
Identity and Access Management is a framework of policies, processes, and technologies designed to ensure the right individuals have appropriate access to resources at the right time. In the SaaS landscape, IAM encompasses several interconnected components that work together to create a secure, scalable identity infrastructure.

At its core, IAM involves three critical functions: authentication (verifying who a user is), authorization (determining what a user can access), and accounting (tracking what users do within your system). For SaaS companies experiencing rapid user growth, these functions become exponentially more complex. A platform managing 100 users operates entirely differently from one supporting 10,000 or 100,000 users, and IAM is the infrastructure that enables this scalability without sacrificing security.

The shift toward cloud-based SaaS models has fundamentally changed how businesses manage identities. Traditional on-premise identity solutions cannot keep pace with the dynamic nature of cloud environments. Modern IAM solutions leverage cloud-native architectures, API-first designs, and AI-driven security to deliver the agility that SaaS companies require.

